The supreme right of taking the auspicia (spectio) belonged to Varro who held the imperium for the day, and Paulus had only the auspicia minora. In later times the higher magis- trate could forbid a lower to note any signs at a time when he wished to aet himself (ne quis mayistratus minor de caelo ser- vasse velit), and there could be no such eollision as in the present case by what was called obnuntiatio or report of unlucky omens to stop proceedings.
